#title
Inline Widgets -- Mobile App Integration Guide

#description
This guide explains how to display Inline ad widgets inside a native iOS or Android mobile app using a standard WebView. In a typical integration, the partner loads its own mobile page or in-app content experience and embeds the Inline widget inside that experience. The main app-side work is configuring the WebView to support a few browser behaviors that native apps sometimes restrict.

::

::page-section
## Quick start

### 1. Load a partner-owned page with placeholder markup

The HTML page loaded in the WebView needs two things: a placeholder `<div>` for each widget and the Inline embed script. This page can be part of the partner's existing mobile web content, a dedicated in-app article template, or another partner-owned content surface.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport"
        content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
</head>
<body>

  <!-- Widget placeholder -->
  <div class="myFinance-widget"
       data-widget-id="6fb33795-3b7b-4128-a70f-f3796d436e96"
       data-campaign="www.transunion.com-other"></div>

  <!-- Inline embed script (provided during onboarding) -->
  <script async src="https://YOURDOMAIN/embed/myFinance.js"></script>

</body>
</html>
```

Replace the widget placeholder with your desired div tag provided to you on the Transunion Integration Documentation guide (under Placeholder Tags) and the Inline embed script with the script(s) provided to you on the Transunion Integration Documentation guide (under Script Integration).

The example above shows the expected structure, but your assigned widget IDs, attributes, and script domain may differ.

### 2. Configure the WebView

#### iOS (WKWebView)

```swift
import WebKit

let config = WKWebViewConfiguration()
config.allowsInlineMediaPlayback = true

// Required: handle window.open() calls from CTA clicks
config.preferences.javaScriptCanOpenWindowsAutomatically = true

let webView = WKWebView(frame: .zero, configuration: config)
webView.uiDelegate = self      // implement createWebViewWith
webView.navigationDelegate = self
```

Implement WKUIDelegate to handle new-window requests:

```swift
func webView(_ webView: WKWebView,
             createWebViewWith configuration: WKWebViewConfiguration,
             for navigationAction: WKNavigationAction,
             windowFeatures: WKWindowFeatures) -> WKWebView? {
    // Open CTA URLs in the system browser
    if let url = navigationAction.request.url {
        UIApplication.shared.open(url)
    }
    return nil
}
```

#### Android (WebView)

```kotlin
val webView = findViewById<WebView>(R.id.webView)
webView.settings.javaScriptEnabled = true
webView.settings.domStorageEnabled = true
webView.settings.setSupportMultipleWindows(true)

// Required: handle window.open() calls from CTA clicks
webView.webChromeClient = object : WebChromeClient() {
    override fun onCreateWindow(
        view: WebView, isDialog: Boolean,
        isUserGesture: Boolean, resultMsg: Message
    ): Boolean {
        val newWebView = WebView(view.context)
        newWebView.webViewClient = object : WebViewClient() {
            override fun shouldOverrideUrlLoading(
                view: WebView, request: WebResourceRequest
            ): Boolean {
                // Open CTA URLs in the system browser
                val intent = Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW, request.url)
                view.context.startActivity(intent)
                return true
            }
        }
        val transport = resultMsg.obj as WebView.WebViewTransport
        transport.webView = newWebView
        resultMsg.sendToTarget()
        return true
    }
}
```

### 3. Verify it works

Load the partner page in the WebView and confirm:

- The widget renders and fills the container width.
- Product listings appear (e.g., mortgage rates, lender names).
- Tapping a CTA button opens the destination URL in the system browser (or in-app browser).

::

