## How it works

```text
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Native App                         │
│  ┌───────────────────────────────┐  │
│  │  WebView                      │  │
│  │  ┌─────────────────────────┐  │  │
│  │  │  Publisher HTML Page    │  │  │
│  │  │  ┌───────────────────┐  │  │  │
│  │  │  │  Embed Script     │  │  │  │
│  │  │  │  (discovers divs, │  │  │  │
│  │  │  │   injects iframes)│  │  │  │
│  │  │  └───────────────────┘  │  │  │
│  │  │  ┌───────────────────┐  │  │  │
│  │  │  │  Widget <iframe>  │  │  │  │
│  │  │  │  (renders rates,  │  │  │  │
│  │  │  │   handles clicks) │  │  │  │
│  │  │  └───────────────────┘  │  │  │
│  │  └─────────────────────────┘  │  │
│  └───────────────────────────────┘  │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
         │
         │  CTA click
         ▼
  System Browser / In-App Browser
  opens advertiser destination URL
```

The embed script scans the page for `<div class="myFinance-widget">` elements.

For each placeholder, it requests widget configuration from the Inline API.

It injects an `<iframe>` that loads the widget (e.g., a mortgage rate table).

The widget fetches live product data and renders inside the iframe.

When a user taps a CTA, the widget sends a message to the embed script, which calls `window.open(url, '_blank')` to navigate.

::

::page-section
## Integration requirements

### Required WebView capabilities

The host WebView must support:

- JavaScript
- DOM storage (localStorage)
- Cross-origin iframe content
- Standard cross-origin XHR / fetch requests
- New-window handling for CTA clicks triggered via `window.open()`
- Navigation initiated by synthetic anchor clicks in fallback flows

### Required network access

The app environment must be able to reach these domains:

| Domain | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `*.myfinance.com` | Embed script, widget content, API calls |
| `*.bankrate.com` | Some widget data sources |
| `cdn.cohesion.tagular.com` | Analytics |

### Consent forwarding

If your app has a consent flow, set consent groups before script load or before a manual re-initialize:

```javascript
window.setMyFinanceUserConsent(['C0001', 'C0002', 'C0004']);
window.initializeMyFinance(true);
```

::

::page-section
## CTA click handling

This is the most important part of the integration.

When a user taps a product CTA (e.g., "See Rates"), the embed script calls `window.open(url, '_blank')`. By default, most mobile WebViews block this call.

Your app must intercept the new-window request and decide where to open it:

| Option | Behavior |
|--------|----------|
| System browser | Opens Safari/Chrome outside the app |
| In-app browser (SFSafariViewController / Custom Tabs) | Opens inside the app with a browser chrome |
| New WebView | Opens in a second WebView managed by the app |

We recommend system browser or in-app browser for the best user experience and to ensure advertiser tracking pixels fire correctly.

::

::page-section
## Consent

If your app collects user consent (GDPR, CCPA), forward the consent groups before initializing the embed:

```javascript
window.setMyFinanceUserConsent(['C0001', 'C0002', 'C0004']);
window.initializeMyFinance(true);
```

::

::page-section
## Validating the integration

Test the integration using the same type of partner-owned page or in-app content surface that will be used in production.

At minimum, confirm:

- The widget renders inside the intended container and fills the available width.
- Product data loads successfully inside the WebView.
- CTA taps open in the system browser or approved in-app browser.
- Returning to the app leaves the partner page and widget in a usable state.
- Required domains are reachable from the app environment.

If your team maintains internal QA pages or debug logging tools, they can be useful for pre-launch validation, but they are not required for the partner integration model described in this guide.

::

::page-section
## FAQ

### Can we use React Native?

Yes. React Native's WebView component is a standard WebView under the hood. Load the partner page (or HTML) and configure the relevant WebView props for JavaScript, storage, and new-window handling. On Android in particular, confirm your WebView layer handles popup or window.open flows rather than assuming ordinary navigation callbacks will catch every CTA path.

### What about Flutter?

The webview_flutter or flutter_inappwebview packages work. Configure the JavaScript and new-window settings as described above.

### Do we need to change anything about the widget itself?

No. Widgets render identically in a WebView and a desktop browser. The only app-side work is ensuring the WebView allows JavaScript, cross-origin iframes, and window.open.

### What if we want embedded lead forms instead of opening a new browser?

Embedded lead form support (ELF) is available as a phase-2 enhancement. It requires additional message-passing between the widget iframe and your native code. Contact your Inline integration contact to discuss requirements.

::

::page-section
## Known limitations (Phase 1)

- Embedded lead forms (open_elf / redirect_elf link targets) are not supported in the initial mobile integration. CTA clicks will fall back to opening the URL in a new window.
- Some institution-specific redirect flows (e.g., Bankrate Hot Pages) are designed for bankrate.com and will fall back to a standard redirect in app contexts.
- Viewable impression tracking depends on the widget iframe receiving visibility information. If the WebView is not visible (e.g., in a background tab), impressions may not fire until the widget scrolls into view.

::
